{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480813"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:51:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:51:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"113"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/113"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.29,0.01,0.14,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"113"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110216"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/113"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"113"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92486"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"181"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1307"},{"type":"tags","id":"2633"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"75"},{"type":"contributions","id":"512"},{"type":"contributions","id":"583"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27117"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41385"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110216"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of increasing abdominal distension and weight gain of 14 kg. He has a medical history of hypertension and takes ramipril sporadically. He does not take any other regular medications. When asked about alcohol consumption, he is evasive and reports drinking \u0027slightly more than usual\u0027 due to work stress. His wife states that he is eating less but still gaining weight. He has trouble climbing up two flights of stairs and rarely walks or exercises.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 165/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has scleral icterus. His abdomen is grossly distended with shifting dullness. Investigations reveal a serum-ascites albumin gradient of 14.8 g/L (\u003E11).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Elevated jugular venous pressure","Splenomegaly","Lymphadenopathy","Hepatic bruit","Asterixis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features of chronic liver disease with portal hypertension, as evidenced by ascites with a high SAAG (14.8 g/L), jaundice, and an evasive alcohol history suggesting alcohol-related liver disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESplenomegaly\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely finding in this patient. Portal hypertension leads to splenic congestion and enlargement, which is present in approximately 50-90% of patients with cirrhosis. The spleen may not be palpable due to the presence of ascites, but would likely be detected on imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElevated jugular venous pressure\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest right heart failure or fluid overload. While cardiac failure can cause ascites with a high SAAG, the presence of jaundice and the clinical context strongly favour liver disease over cardiac pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphadenopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is not a typical feature of cirrhosis. It might be present in malignancy or infections such as tuberculosis, but these conditions would typically cause ascites with a low SAAG rather than the high SAAG seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatic bruit\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare finding that may occur with hepatocellular carcinoma or acute alcoholic hepatitis. It is not a common feature of cirrhosis and would not be expected in most patients with chronic liver disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAsterixis\u003C/strong\u003E (flapping tremor) is a sign of hepatic encephalopathy, which occurs in advanced liver disease. While possible in cirrhosis, it typically develops later in the disease course when there is significant hepatic decompensation. This patient shows no clinical evidence of encephalopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of portal hypertension (evidenced by high SAAG ascites) and chronic liver disease makes splenomegaly the most likely additional finding among the options provided.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The serum-ascites albumin gradient (SAAG) \u003E11 g/L indicates portal hypertension as the cause of ascites.","Clinical features of cirrhosis include jaundice, spider naevi, and ascites.","Portal hypertension in cirrhosis leads to splenomegaly due to splenic congestion."],"references":["Hou W, Sanyal AJ. Ascites: Diagnosis and Management. Med Clin N AM 2009; 93:801-17. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19577115/","Walsh K, Alexander G. Alcoholic liver disease. Postgrad Med J. 2000;76:280-86. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1741594/","Schuppan D, Afdhal NH. Liver cirrhosis. Lancet. 2008;371(9615):838-851. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18328931/","Aydinli M, Bayraktar Y. Budd-Chiari syndrome: etiology, pathogenesis and diagnosis. World J Gastroenterol. 2007;13(19):2693-2696. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17569137/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92486"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"113"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92486"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-28T22:31:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-28T22:38:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"113"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110216"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":